@node sect0 "Name"
iconv_open - allocate descriptor for character set conversion 
@endnode

@node sect1 "Synopsis"

@{code}#include <iconv.h>
iconv_t iconv_open (const char* tocode, const char* fromcode);@{body}

@endnode

@node sect2 "@{ub}Description"
The @{b}iconv_open@{ub} function allocates a conversion descriptor suitable for converting byte sequences from character encoding @{i}fromcode@{ui} to character encoding @{i}tocode@{ui}. The values permitted for @{i}fromcode@{ui} and @{i}tocode@{ui} and the supported combinations are system dependent. For the libiconv library, the following encodings are supported, in all combinations. 



 European languages @{lindent 3}

@{code}@{body}
ASCII, ISO-8859-{1,2,3,4,5,7,9,10,13,14,15,16}, KOI8-R, KOI8-U, KOI8-RU, CP{1250,1251,1252,1253,1254,1257}, CP{850,866,1131}, Mac{Roman,CentralEurope,Iceland,Croatian,Romania}, Mac{Cyrillic,Ukraine,Greek,Turkish}, Macintosh @{lindent 0}

 Semitic languages @{lindent 3}

@{code}@{body}
ISO-8859-{6,8}, CP{1255,1256}, CP862, Mac{Hebrew,Arabic} @{lindent 0}

 Japanese @{lindent 3}

@{code}@{body}
EUC-JP, SHIFT_JIS, CP932, ISO-2022-JP, ISO-2022-JP-2, ISO-2022-JP-1 @{lindent 0}

 Chinese @{lindent 3}

@{code}@{body}
EUC-CN, HZ, GBK, CP936, GB18030, EUC-TW, BIG5, CP950, BIG5-HKSCS, BIG5-HKSCS:2001, BIG5-HKSCS:1999, ISO-2022-CN, ISO-2022-CN-EXT @{lindent 0}

 Korean @{lindent 3}

@{code}@{body}
EUC-KR, CP949, ISO-2022-KR, JOHAB @{lindent 0}

 Armenian @{lindent 3}

@{code}@{body}
ARMSCII-8 @{lindent 0}

 Georgian @{lindent 3}

@{code}@{body}
Georgian-Academy, Georgian-PS @{lindent 0}

 Tajik @{lindent 3}

@{code}@{body}
KOI8-T @{lindent 0}

 Kazakh @{lindent 3}

@{code}@{body}
PT154, RK1048 @{lindent 0}

 Thai @{lindent 3}

@{code}@{body}
TIS-620, CP874, MacThai @{lindent 0}

 Laotian @{lindent 3}

@{code}@{body}
MuleLao-1, CP1133 @{lindent 0}

 Vietnamese @{lindent 3}

@{code}@{body}
VISCII, TCVN, CP1258 @{lindent 0}

 Platform specifics @{lindent 3}

@{code}@{body}
HP-ROMAN8, NEXTSTEP @{lindent 0}

 Full Unicode @{lindent 3}

@{code}@{body}
UTF-8 
@{code}@{body}
UCS-2, UCS-2BE, UCS-2LE 
@{code}@{body}
UCS-4, UCS-4BE, UCS-4LE 
@{code}@{body}
UTF-16, UTF-16BE, UTF-16LE 
@{code}@{body}
UTF-32, UTF-32BE, UTF-32LE 
@{code}@{body}
UTF-7 
@{code}@{body}
C99, JAVA @{lindent 0}

 Full Unicode, in terms of @{b}uint16_t@{ub} or @{b}uint32_t@{ub} @{lindent 3}
(with machine dependent endianness and alignment) 
@{code}@{body}
UCS-2-INTERNAL, UCS-4-INTERNAL @{lindent 0}

 Locale dependent, in terms of @{b}char@{ub} or @{b}wchar_t@{ub} @{lindent 3}
(with machine dependent endianness and alignment, and with semantics depending on the OS and the current LC_CTYPE locale facet) 
@{code}@{body}
char, wchar_t @{lindent 0}

When configured with the option @{b}--enable-extra-encodings@{ub}, it also provides support for a few extra encodings: 



 European languages @{lindent 3}

@{code}CP{437,737,775,852,853,855,857,858,860,861,863,865,869,1125}
@{body}
@{lindent 0}

 Semitic languages @{lindent 3}

@{code}@{body}
CP864 @{lindent 0}

 Japanese @{lindent 3}

@{code}@{body}
EUC-JISX0213, Shift_JISX0213, ISO-2022-JP-3 @{lindent 0}

 Chinese @{lindent 3}

@{code}@{body}
BIG5-2003 (experimental) @{lindent 0}

 Turkmen @{lindent 3}

@{code}@{body}
TDS565 @{lindent 0}

 Platform specifics @{lindent 3}

@{code}@{body}
ATARIST, RISCOS-LATIN1 @{lindent 0}

The empty encoding name "" is equivalent to "char": it denotes the locale dependent character encoding. 

When the string "//TRANSLIT" is appended to @{i}tocode@{ui}, transliteration is activated. This means that when a character cannot be represented in the target character set, it can be approximated through one or several characters that look similar to the original character. 

When the string "//IGNORE" is appended to @{i}tocode@{ui}, characters that cannot be represented in the target character set will be silently discarded. 

The resulting conversion descriptor can be used with @{b}iconv@{ub} any number of times. It remains valid until deallocated using @{b}iconv_close@{ub}. 

A conversion descriptor contains a conversion state. After creation using @{b}iconv_open@{ub}, the state is in the initial state. Using @{b}iconv@{ub} modifies the descriptor's conversion state. (This implies that a conversion descriptor can not be used in multiple threads simultaneously.) To bring the state back to the initial state, use @{b}iconv@{ub} with NULL as @{i}inbuf@{ui} argument. 


@endnode

@node sect3 "Return Value"
The @{b}iconv_open@{ub} function returns a freshly allocated conversion descriptor. In case of error, it sets @{b}errno@{ub} and returns (iconv_t)(-1). 
@endnode

@node sect4 "Errors"
The following error can occur, among others: 

 @{b}EINVAL@{ub} @{lindent 3}
The conversion from @{i}fromcode@{ui} to @{i}tocode@{ui} is not supported by the implementation. @{lindent 0}


@endnode

